result.execSummary:
The defendant Rebecca M Zimmermann was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Receiving or Concealing Stolen Property (<=$2500), a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.34(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Rebecca M Zimmermann in court with attorney Alexis Liggins.  Taylor L. Kraus appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk ssm.  

Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court found the state has satisfied victims' rights law.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 day in the House of Correction with credit for 1 day served FOR A TIME SERVED DISPOSITION.

Court ordered defendant to pay ALL COSTS and SURCHARGES commencing February 11, 2016 at the rate of $25.00 per month or, as a penalty if not paid, convert to a civil judgment.
If the defendant commits no new crimes, Court will grant expungement after 1 year.
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief received and filed.
